{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\nStamp denormalized author identity (name + email) plus an OPTIONAL `author_id`\n(referencing a ddbe `identity`) onto EVERY mutating event's envelope, without\nbreaking replay of pre-change events. Substrate for authorship attestation (bde5)\nand enforcement (3183).\n\n## Why\nAuthorship certification needs each event to record who wrote it in a replication-\nand compaction-durable form (denormalized), with an optional link to the rich\n`identity` entity when one resolves (identity is opt-in).\n\n## What\n### 1. Shared attribution helper (`src/rebar/_commands/_seam.py`)\n- Extract `_git_config(key, fallback=\"\") -> str` from the existing `author()`\n  (which shells `git config user.name`); reimplement `author()` on it and add\n  `author_email()` = `_git_config(\"user.email\", \"\")`. Strip; return fallback on\n  unset / OSError / non-zero; NEVER raise.\n- Add `attribution_fields(repo_root=None) -> dict`: returns\n  `{\"author_email\": author_email()}`, plus `{\"author_id\": <id>}` ONLY when\n  `identity.resolve_current_identity(repo_root=repo_root)` (real signature is\n  keyword-only `(*, repo_root=None)` per ddbe) returns non-None; the key is OMITTED\n  when None. MEMOIZE per resolved `repo_root` for the process lifetime in ONE cache\n  entry covering BOTH the git-email lookup AND the identity scan, so N writes do at\n  most ONE git-email call and ONE identity scan total.\n\n### 2. Stamp at ALL envelope-composing sites (the \"single seam\" is actually three)\nMerge `attribution_fields(repo_root)` into the envelope next to the existing\n`\"author\"` key at every site that COMPOSES an event envelope (verified list —\n`author_email` always present, `author_id` present-only):\n- `_seam.py::append_event` — create/edit/link/comment/tag/sign/... AND its batch-sink\n  branch (add BEFORE the sink so buffered events are byte-identical).\n- `_commands/txn.py` — `transition_core` (STATUS event, ~line 276) and `claim_core`\n  (STATUS ~445 AND EDIT ~464); these build envelopes directly and already have the\n  `author` name in scope.\n- `_commands/delete.py` — `_write_unlink` (~112) and `_write_event` (~202)\n  (STATUS-deleted / ARCHIVED / UNLINK envelopes built directly).\nEach of these already computes/receives an `author` name; add the email/id via the\nshared helper (pass the `repo_root`/tracker they already hold).\n\n### 3. Replay back-compat (reducer surfaces PRESENT-ONLY, matching where `author` lives)\nSurface the new fields **present-only** (mirrors `source_*`), at the SAME structural\nlocation each processor already puts `author` — verified sites:\n- `process_create` (_processors.py:59) stamps TOP-LEVEL `state[\"author\"]` → also set\n  TOP-LEVEL `state[\"author_email\"]`/`state[\"author_id\"]` present-only. This is the\n  ticket-author attribution bde5 reads.\n- `process_comment` (:248) puts `author` on the per-comment `_entry` dict → add\n  `author_email`/`author_id` present-only ON THAT ENTRY (not top-level).\n- `process_revert` (:374) puts `author` on the per-revert record → add them THERE.\n- `process_signature` (:494) puts `author` on the signature record → add them THERE.\n(`process_edit`/`process_status` do NOT stamp author and are NOT touched.)\nConsequences:\n- A pre-change event (no author_email/author_id) reduces to BYTE-IDENTICAL compiled\n  state — no new keys anywhere — so \"same state\" holds exactly, no missing-key crash.\n- A new CREATE surfaces top-level `author_email` (always) + `author_id` (when\n  resolved); bde5 reads them off top-level state.\n- SNAPSHOT: `process_snapshot` restores compiled_state verbatim, so post-change\n  snapshots carry the fields additively; older reducers ignore unknown state keys —\n  no special handling.\n\n## Scope\nIn: the helpers + cache, envelope stamping at the 3 composer modules, reducer\npresent-only surfacing at the 4 processors, and the back-compat + every-path +\ncache tests. Out: signing/verifying (bde5), key lifecycle (e165), enforcement\n(3183). `author_id` is populated, NOT verified or required here.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] EVERY mutating path carries `author` + `author_email` in the raw stored event:\n  a test exercises `create`, `comment`, a `transition`/`claim` (txn.py), and a\n  `delete`/archive (delete.py) and asserts each resulting event JSON contains\n  `author_email`, proving all envelope composers stamp it (not just append_event).\n- [ ] With a current identity set (`rebar identity use <id>`): a CREATE carries\n  `author_id == <id>` in the raw event AND top-level reduced state surfaces\n  `author_id`/`author_email`. With NO identity: the `author_id` key is ABSENT from\n  both raw event and reduced state (test both branches).\n- [ ] Back-compat: a hand-authored event stream WITHOUT author_email/author_id\n  reduces without error to compiled state containing NEITHER key anywhere\n  (top-level or sub-records) — byte-identical to pre-change — asserted by diffing\n  the reduced dict of a synthetic pre-change stream.\n- [ ] `author_email()` returns `\"\"` (never raises) when `git config user.email` is\n  unset or the git call fails — tested by forcing the subprocess to error.\n- [ ] Caching: across N sequential writes in one process, BOTH the git-email lookup\n  AND the identity scan run at most once each — asserted with TWO independent\n  call-counters (one on the git-email call, one on `resolve_current_identity`).\n\n## file_impact\n- `src/rebar/_commands/_seam.py` (_git_config + author_email + attribution_fields + cache + append_event stamping)\n- `src/rebar/_commands/txn.py` (stamp transition_core + claim_core STATUS/EDIT envelopes)\n- `src/rebar/_commands/delete.py` (stamp _write_unlink + _write_event envelopes)\n- `src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py` (present-only surfacing: top-level at process_create; per-entry at comment/revert/signature)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783822335662805001,"uuid":"841fa023-9f4e-4111-a801-0c46eeba7676"}